Earl of Winchester 1207–65. Descendants of this family later bore the name <i>Quincey</i> up to the time of the English essayist Thomas <i>De Quincey</i> (1785–1859), who changed his name from <i>Quincey</i> to <i>De Quincey</i> in 1796.","History: The American Quincy family were established in MA by Edmund Quincy in 1633. Fifth in descent was Josiah Quincy (1744–75), a leading patriot, who was sent to England to argue the colonists’ case in 1774. His son Josiah (1772–1864) was a powerful opponent of slavery, president of Harvard, and mayor of Boston, a post also held by several of his descendants. The traditional pronunciation is “Quinzy”."],"variants":[{"name":"Quincey","meanings":["English: variant of   Quincy  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel de Quincy was born in 1224. She married Alasdair Comyn before 1260, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1282, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1224–1282":"1224–1282","1217–1289":"1217–1289","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1305":"1305","1217":"1217","1224":"1224","1289":"1289","before 1260":"enne 1260","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","Europe":"Europe","Tottenham, Middlesex, England":"Tottenham, Middlesex, England"},"fi":{"1224–1282":"1224–1282","1217–1289":"1217–1289","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1305":"1305","1217":"1217","1224":"1224","1289":"1289","before 1260":"ennen vuotta 1260","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","Europe":"Europe","Tottenham, Middlesex, England":"Tottenham, Middlesex, England"},"fr":{"1224–1282":"1224–1282","1217–1289":"1217–1289","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1305":"1305","1217":"1217","1224":"1224","1289":"1289","before 1260":"av